    source: CORTEX_STEP_SOURCE_USER_EXPLICIT
    source_trajectory_step_info {
      trajectory_id: "977ca7d7-054c-4d86-b499-fcd59cf4bc49"
      step_index: 1
      cascade_id: "977ca7d7-054c-4d86-b499-fcd59cf4bc49"
    }
  }
  user_input {
    user_response: "Here\'s the full rewritten prompt:\n\n---\n\nYou are an elite Software Architect and Senior Full-Stack Engineer specializing in AI tooling, lightweight proxies, and resilient API design.\n\nYour task is to generate the complete, production-ready source code for a lightweight, OpenAI-compatible proxy server written in Node.js (TypeScript).\n\n---\n\n### PROJECT PHILOSOPHY & DIFFERENTIATION\n\nUnlike complex infrastructure tools like LiteLLM which require databases and Docker setups, this project is a **\"Zero-Config, Self-Healing Free-Tier Maximizer\"** designed for content creators and indie hackers. It runs locally or on edge functions, aggregates free-tier endpoints, and automatically handles failovers silently \342\200\224 but only when it is safe to do so.\n\n---\n\n### CORE ARCHITECTURAL REQUIREMENTS\n\n#### 1. INPUT ENDPOINT\nExpose a single local endpoint: `POST /v1/chat/completions`\n\nThis endpoint must be fully compliant with the standard OpenAI API specification, including:\n- Standard (non-streaming) JSON responses\n- Streaming responses via Server-Sent Events (`stream: true`)\n\nUse **Hono** as the HTTP framework. It is TypeScript-native, zero-overhead, and runs cleanly on Node.js via `@hono/node-server`.\n\n#### 2. THE CASCADE ROUTER\nWhen a request arrives, the proxy **completely ignores the model string sent by the client** and instead routes the request through a prioritized cascade of free-tier API configurations:\n\n- **Priority 1 \342\200\224 OpenRouter** (`OPENROUTER_API_KEY`): Use model `meta-llama/llama-3-8b-instruct:free`\n- **Priority 2 \342\200\224 Hugging Face Serverless Inference API** (`HF_API_KEY`): Use model `mistralai/Mistral-7B-Instruct-v0.2` by default, overridable via `HF_MODEL_ID` env var. Translate the OpenAI `messages` array into the HuggingFace chat template format before sending.\n- **Priority 3 \342\200\224 Google Gemini** (`GEMINI_API_KEY`): Use model `gemini-1.5-flash`. Translate the OpenAI `messages` array into the Gemini `contents` format before sending.\n- **Priority 4 \342\200\224 Paid Fallback** (`FALLBACK_API_KEY`, `FALLBACK_BASE_URL`, `FALLBACK_MODEL`): An optional last-resort paid endpoint that is OpenAI-API-compatible. Skip this tier entirely if these env vars are not set.\n\nLog the originally requested model string alongside which tier actually handled the request, so users can debug routing behavior.\n\n#### 3. SELF-HEALING CASCADE LOGIC\nIf a tier fails for any of the following reasons, immediately catch the exception, log the failure with the tier name and reason, and trigger the next tier in the cascade for the **same original request**:\n\n- HTTP 429 (rate limit)\n- HTTP 503 (service unavailable)\n- HTTP 401 / 403 (auth or quota error)\n- Network error or fetch rejection\n- **Per-tier timeout exceeded** (see requirement 5)\n\nIf **all tiers fail**, return a structured JSON error to the client:\n```json\n{\n  \"error\": {\n    \"message\": \"All tiers exhausted. See server logs for details.\",\n    \"type\": \"proxy_error\",\n    \"tiers_attempted\": [\"openrouter\", \"huggingface\", \"gemini\"]\n  }\n}\n```\n\n#### 4. STREAMING RESILIENCY \342\200\224 EXPLICIT RULES\nStreaming fallback behavior must follow these exact rules:\n\n- **If a streaming tier fails BEFORE the first byte is flushed to the client:** silently catch the error, log it, and attempt the next tier. The client sees nothing and the response begins from the next tier.\n- **If a streaming tier fails AFTER streaming has already begun (first chunk already sent):** do NOT attempt to continue from the next tier. Instead, flush a final SSE chunk containing an inline error notice, then send `data: [DONE]` and close the stream. Log the failure. Example final chunk format:\n```\ndata: {\"id\":\"chatcmpl-error\",\"object\":\"chat.completion.chunk\",\"choices\":[{\"delta\":{\"content\":\"\\n\\n[proxy: upstream disconnected, response may be incomplete]\"},\"finish_reason\":\"stop\",\"index\":0}]}\n\ndata: [DONE]\n```\n\n#### 5. PER-TIER TIMEOUTS\nEvery upstream fetch must be wrapped in a `Promise.race` against an `AbortController`-based timeout.\n\n- Default timeout: **15 seconds per tier**\n- Configurable via environment variable: `TIER_TIMEOUT_MS`\n- A timeout counts as a failure and triggers the cascade to the next tier\n\n#### 6. REQUEST LOGGING\nFor every request, emit a structured log line after resolution containing:\n- Timestamp\n- Originally requested model (from client)\n- Tier that successfully handled the request (or \"all_failed\")\n- Latency in milliseconds\n- Success or failure reason\n\nExample:\n```\n[2024-01-15T10:23:01Z] model_requested=gpt-4o tier_used=gemini latency_ms=1243 status=success\n[2024-01-15T10:23:05Z] model_requested=gpt-4 tier_used=all_failed latency_ms=45021 status=error reason=\"all tiers exhausted\"\n```\n\n---\n\n### ENVIRONMENT VARIABLES\n\n| Variable | Required | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| `OPENROUTER_API_KEY` | Optional | Enables Tier 1 |\n| `HF_API_KEY` | Optional | Enables Tier 2 |\n| `HF_MODEL_ID` | Optional | Overrides HF model (default: `mistralai/Mistral-7B-Instruct-v0.2`) |\n| `GEMINI_API_KEY` | Optional | Enables Tier 3 |\n| `FALLBACK_API_KEY` | Optional | Enables Tier 4 |\n| `FALLBACK_BASE_URL` | Optional | Base URL for Tier 4 (e.g. `https://api.openai.com`) |\n| `FALLBACK_MODEL` | Optional | Model string for Tier 4 |\n| `TIER_TIMEOUT_MS` | Optional | Per-tier fetch timeout in ms (default: `15000`) |\n| `PORT` | Optional | Server port (default: `8080`) |\n\nAny tier whose required key is missing must be **skipped silently** (not errored) during the cascade.\n\n---\n\n### EXPECTED FILE OUTPUT\n\nProvide the complete codebase with these exact files. Do not use placeholders. Write every function in full.\n\n#### `package.json`\n- Include `hono`, `@hono/node-server` as dependencies\n- Include `typescript`, `tsx`, `@types/node` as devDependencies\n- Include scripts: `dev` (runs with `tsx`), `build` (compiles with `tsc`), `start` (runs compiled output)\n\n#### `tsconfig.json`\n- Target `ES2022`, module `NodeNext`, strict mode on\n\n#### `src/types.ts`\nDefine TypeScript interfaces for:\n- OpenAI `ChatCompletionRequest` (messages, model, stream, temperature, max_tokens)\n- OpenAI `ChatCompletionResponse` (full non-streaming)\n- OpenAI `ChatCompletionChunk` (streaming SSE chunk)\n- `TierConfig` \342\200\224 describes a single cascade tier (name, enabled, execute function signature)\n- `TierResult` \342\200\224 wraps a successful response with metadata (tier name, latency)\n- `ProxyError` \342\200\224 structured error returned when all tiers fail\n\n#### `src/adapters/openrouter.ts`\nFull implementation of the OpenRouter tier. Handles both streaming and non-streaming. Passes the OpenAI payload through largely as-is since OpenRouter is OpenAI-compatible.\n\n#### `src/adapters/huggingface.ts`\nFull implementation of the HuggingFace tier. Must translate the OpenAI `messages` array into HuggingFace\'s expected chat format. Handle the response and normalize it back to OpenAI response shape for non-streaming. For streaming, translate HuggingFace\'s SSE token format into OpenAI-compatible SSE chunks.\n\n#### `src/adapters/gemini.ts`\nFull implementation of the Gemini tier. Must translate the OpenAI `messages` array into Gemini\'s `contents` format (with `role: user/model` and `parts: [{text}]`). Handle the response and normalize it back to OpenAI response shape for non-streaming. For streaming, translate Gemini\'s streaming format into OpenAI-compatible SSE chunks.\n\n#### `src/adapters/fallback.ts`\nFull implementation of the optional paid fallback tier. It is OpenAI-API-compatible, so pass the payload through directly, substituting the model string with `FALLBACK_MODEL`. Skip gracefully if env vars are not set.\n\n#### `src/router.ts`\nThe core cascade engine:\n- Builds the ordered list of enabled tiers at startup (skipping any with missing keys)\n- Implements `executeWithTimeout(fetchFn, timeoutMs)` using `Promise.race` and `AbortController`\n- Implements the main `routeRequest(request, honoContext)` function that:\n  - Iterates through tiers in order\n  - For streaming: tracks whether the first byte has been flushed, and applies the correct fallback rule from requirement 4\n  - For non-streaming: retries the next tier on any failure\n  - Emits the structured log line after resolution\n\n#### `src/server.ts`\n- Spins up a Hono app on `@hono/node-server`\n- Registers `POST /v1/chat/completions`\n- Parses and validates the incoming request body\n- Calls `routeRequest` and pipes the result back to the client\n- Sets correct response headers (`Content-Type: text/event-stream` for streaming, `application/json` otherwise)\n- Handles and returns structured errors for malformed requests (missing `messages`, etc.)\n\n---\n\n### FINAL INSTRUCTIONS\n\n- Use native `fetch` (Node 18+) for all HTTP calls. No `axios` or `node-fetch`.\n- All files must be complete. No \"TODO\", no \"implement this yourself\", no omitted sections.\n- Code must be heavily commented, explaining *why* decisions are made, not just what.\n- The cascade, timeout, and streaming resiliency logic in `router.ts` are the heart of this project \342\200\224 treat them with the most care and verbosity.\n\n---\n\nThis should now produce output that\'s architecturally sound with no ambiguous edge cases left for the model to guess at. The streaming resiliency rules and timeout spec in particular will save you a lot of debugging time."
    items {
      text: "Here\'s the full rewritten prompt:\n\n---\n\nYou are an elite Software Architect and Senior Full-Stack Engineer specializing in AI tooling, lightweight proxies, and resilient API design.\n\nYour task is to generate the complete, production-ready source code for a lightweight, OpenAI-compatible proxy server written in Node.js (TypeScript).\n\n---\n\n### PROJECT PHILOSOPHY & DIFFERENTIATION\n\nUnlike complex infrastructure tools like LiteLLM which require databases and Docker setups, this project is a **\"Zero-Config, Self-Healing Free-Tier Maximizer\"** designed for content creators and indie hackers. It runs locally or on edge functions, aggregates free-tier endpoints, and automatically handles failovers silently \342\200\224 but only when it is safe to do so.\n\n---\n\n### CORE ARCHITECTURAL REQUIREMENTS\n\n#### 1. INPUT ENDPOINT\nExpose a single local endpoint: `POST /v1/chat/completions`\n\nThis endpoint must be fully compliant with the standard OpenAI API specification, including:\n- Standard (non-streaming) JSON responses\n- Streaming responses via Server-Sent Events (`stream: true`)\n\nUse **Hono** as the HTTP framework. It is TypeScript-native, zero-overhead, and runs cleanly on Node.js via `@hono/node-server`.\n\n#### 2. THE CASCADE ROUTER\nWhen a request arrives, the proxy **completely ignores the model string sent by the client** and instead routes the request through a prioritized cascade of free-tier API configurations:\n\n- **Priority 1 \342\200\224 OpenRouter** (`OPENROUTER_API_KEY`): Use model `meta-llama/llama-3-8b-instruct:free`\n- **Priority 2 \342\200\224 Hugging Face Serverless Inference API** (`HF_API_KEY`): Use model `mistralai/Mistral-7B-Instruct-v0.2` by default, overridable via `HF_MODEL_ID` env var. Translate the OpenAI `messages` array into the HuggingFace chat template format before sending.\n- **Priority 3 \342\200\224 Google Gemini** (`GEMINI_API_KEY`): Use model `gemini-1.5-flash`. Translate the OpenAI `messages` array into the Gemini `contents` format before sending.\n- **Priority 4 \342\200\224 Paid Fallback** (`FALLBACK_API_KEY`, `FALLBACK_BASE_URL`, `FALLBACK_MODEL`): An optional last-resort paid endpoint that is OpenAI-API-compatible. Skip this tier entirely if these env vars are not set.\n\nLog the originally requested model string alongside which tier actually handled the request, so users can debug routing behavior.\n\n#### 3. SELF-HEALING CASCADE LOGIC\nIf a tier fails for any of the following reasons, immediately catch the exception, log the failure with the tier name and reason, and trigger the next tier in the cascade for the **same original request**:\n\n- HTTP 429 (rate limit)\n- HTTP 503 (service unavailable)\n- HTTP 401 / 403 (auth or quota error)\n- Network error or fetch rejection\n- **Per-tier timeout exceeded** (see requirement 5)\n\nIf **all tiers fail**, return a structured JSON error to the client:\n```json\n{\n  \"error\": {\n    \"message\": \"All tiers exhausted. See server logs for details.\",\n    \"type\": \"proxy_error\",\n    \"tiers_attempted\": [\"openrouter\", \"huggingface\", \"gemini\"]\n  }\n}\n```\n\n#### 4. STREAMING RESILIENCY \342\200\224 EXPLICIT RULES\nStreaming fallback behavior must follow these exact rules:\n\n- **If a streaming tier fails BEFORE the first byte is flushed to the client:** silently catch the error, log it, and attempt the next tier. The client sees nothing and the response begins from the next tier.\n- **If a streaming tier fails AFTER streaming has already begun (first chunk already sent):** do NOT attempt to continue from the next tier. Instead, flush a final SSE chunk containing an inline error notice, then send `data: [DONE]` and close the stream. Log the failure. Example final chunk format:\n```\ndata: {\"id\":\"chatcmpl-error\",\"object\":\"chat.completion.chunk\",\"choices\":[{\"delta\":{\"content\":\"\\n\\n[proxy: upstream disconnected, response may be incomplete]\"},\"finish_reason\":\"stop\",\"index\":0}]}\n\ndata: [DONE]\n```\n\n#### 5. PER-TIER TIMEOUTS\nEvery upstream fetch must be wrapped in a `Promise.race` against an `AbortController`-based timeout.\n\n- Default timeout: **15 seconds per tier**\n- Configurable via environment variable: `TIER_TIMEOUT_MS`\n- A timeout counts as a failure and triggers the cascade to the next tier\n\n#### 6. REQUEST LOGGING\nFor every request, emit a structured log line after resolution containing:\n- Timestamp\n- Originally requested model (from client)\n- Tier that successfully handled the request (or \"all_failed\")\n- Latency in milliseconds\n- Success or failure reason\n\nExample:\n```\n[2024-01-15T10:23:01Z] model_requested=gpt-4o tier_used=gemini latency_ms=1243 status=success\n[2024-01-15T10:23:05Z] model_requested=gpt-4 tier_used=all_failed latency_ms=45021 status=error reason=\"all tiers exhausted\"\n```\n\n---\n\n### ENVIRONMENT VARIABLES\n\n| Variable | Required | Description |\n|---|---|---|\n| `OPENROUTER_API_KEY` | Optional | Enables Tier 1 |\n| `HF_API_KEY` | Optional | Enables Tier 2 |\n| `HF_MODEL_ID` | Optional | Overrides HF model (default: `mistralai/Mistral-7B-Instruct-v0.2`) |\n| `GEMINI_API_KEY` | Optional | Enables Tier 3 |\n| `FALLBACK_API_KEY` | Optional | Enables Tier 4 |\n| `FALLBACK_BASE_URL` | Optional | Base URL for Tier 4 (e.g. `https://api.openai.com`) |\n| `FALLBACK_MODEL` | Optional | Model string for Tier 4 |\n| `TIER_TIMEOUT_MS` | Optional | Per-tier fetch timeout in ms (default: `15000`) |\n| `PORT` | Optional | Server port (default: `8080`) |\n\nAny tier whose required key is missing must be **skipped silently** (not errored) during the cascade.\n\n---\n\n### EXPECTED FILE OUTPUT\n\nProvide the complete codebase with these exact files. Do not use placeholders. Write every function in full.\n\n#### `package.json`\n- Include `hono`, `@hono/node-server` as dependencies\n- Include `typescript`, `tsx`, `@types/node` as devDependencies\n- Include scripts: `dev` (runs with `tsx`), `build` (compiles with `tsc`), `start` (runs compiled output)\n\n#### `tsconfig.json`\n- Target `ES2022`, module `NodeNext`, strict mode on\n\n#### `src/types.ts`\nDefine TypeScript interfaces for:\n- OpenAI `ChatCompletionRequest` (messages, model, stream, temperature, max_tokens)\n- OpenAI `ChatCompletionResponse` (full non-streaming)\n- OpenAI `ChatCompletionChunk` (streaming SSE chunk)\n- `TierConfig` \342\200\224 describes a single cascade tier (name, enabled, execute function signature)\n- `TierResult` \342\200\224 wraps a successful response with metadata (tier name, latency)\n- `ProxyError` \342\200\224 structured error returned when all tiers fail\n\n#### `src/adapters/openrouter.ts`\nFull implementation of the OpenRouter tier. Handles both streaming and non-streaming. Passes the OpenAI payload through largely as-is since OpenRouter is OpenAI-compatible.\n\n#### `src/adapters/huggingface.ts`\nFull implementation of the HuggingFace tier. Must translate the OpenAI `messages` array into HuggingFace\'s expected chat format. Handle the response and normalize it back to OpenAI response shape for non-streaming. For streaming, translate HuggingFace\'s SSE token format into OpenAI-compatible SSE chunks.\n\n#### `src/adapters/gemini.ts`\nFull implementation of the Gemini tier. Must translate the OpenAI `messages` array into Gemini\'s `contents` format (with `role: user/model` and `parts: [{text}]`). Handle the response and normalize it back to OpenAI response shape for non-streaming. For streaming, translate Gemini\'s streaming format into OpenAI-compatible SSE chunks.\n\n#### `src/adapters/fallback.ts`\nFull implementation of the optional paid fallback tier. It is OpenAI-API-compatible, so pass the payload through directly, substituting the model string with `FALLBACK_MODEL`. Skip gracefully if env vars are not set.\n\n#### `src/router.ts`\nThe core cascade engine:\n- Builds the ordered list of enabled tiers at startup (skipping any with missing keys)\n- Implements `executeWithTimeout(fetchFn, timeoutMs)` using `Promise.race` and `AbortController`\n- Implements the main `routeRequest(request, honoContext)` function that:\n  - Iterates through tiers in order\n  - For streaming: tracks whether the first byte has been flushed, and applies the correct fallback rule from requirement 4\n  - For non-streaming: retries the next tier on any failure\n  - Emits the structured log line after resolution\n\n#### `src/server.ts`\n- Spins up a Hono app on `@hono/node-server`\n- Registers `POST /v1/chat/completions`\n- Parses and validates the incoming request body\n- Calls `routeRequest` and pipes the result back to the client\n- Sets correct response headers (`Content-Type: text/event-stream` for streaming, `application/json` otherwise)\n- Handles and returns structured errors for malformed requests (missing `messages`, etc.)\n\n---\n\n### FINAL INSTRUCTIONS\n\n- Use native `fetch` (Node 18+) for all HTTP calls. No `axios` or `node-fetch`.\n- All files must be complete. No \"TODO\", no \"implement this yourself\", no omitted sections.\n- Code must be heavily commented, explaining *why* decisions are made, not just what.\n- The cascade, timeout, and streaming resiliency logic in `router.ts` are the heart of this project \342\200\224 treat them with the most care and verbosity.\n\n---\n\nThis should now produce output that\'s architecturally sound with no ambiguous edge cases left for the model to guess at. The streaming resiliency rules and timeout spec in particular will save you a lot of debugging time."
    }
  }
}
